(89, 54, '2017-05-26 17:17:29', 'Journalist Jenny Valentish investigates the female experience of drugs and alcohol, using her own story to light the way. Her travels around Australia take her to treatment facilities and AA groups. Mining the expertise of leading researchers, she explores the early predictors of addiction, such as childhood trauma and temperament, and teenage impulsivity.Drawing on neuroscience, she explains why other self-destructive behaviours â such as eating disorders, compulsive buying and high-risk sex â are interchangeable with problematic substance use.Valentish follows the pathways that women, in particular, take into addiction â and out again. Woman of Substances is an insightful, rigorous and brutally honest read.âValentish mixes her own careening story with some truly fabulous research. This book taught me things I wasnât expecting about the landscape of substance use.â âKate HoldenâA compelling blend of the sociology, psychology and physiology that drives female addiction, seasoned by the authorâs self-serrating humour and remarkable skill.â âProfessor Marc Lewis, Ph.D., Professor Emeritus, University of Toronto. Author of The Biology of Desire (2015) and Memoirs of an Addicted Brain (2011)âA fabulous read. Raw, revealing, at times heartbreaking, but searingly honest and clearly aimed to support anyone who is wondering if they will ever recover from addiction. Yes, says Jenny, you can: just don&#39;t expect unicorns to visit immediately. Beautifully written, it prompts a broader discussion around the role women&#39;s (little-discussed) hormones can play in one&#39;s âaddiction and recovery storyâ, and how rarely this has been considered when it comes to models of recovery. Jenny tells a truly hopeful story about one woman who has come to terms with who she is. She looks the beast in the eyes. Well done.â âClare Bowditch,âJenny Valentish takes us on a field trip through her vulnerabilities and then, like a tour guide in a foreign land, flag aloft, she provides a path back from the abyss. This is an enormously compelling, confronting and informative piece on addiction and recovery from a female perspective. I know a lot of people I want to give this book to.â âDeborah Conway', 'Woman of Substances - Books on Google Play', 'Publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'woman-of-substances-books-on-google-play', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'link', 0, 1, 0, 'https://play.google.com/store/books/details/Jenny_Valentish_Woman_of_Substances?id=tXXRDgAAQBAJ', NULL, 'https://books.google.com/books/content/images/frontcover/tXXRDgAAQBAJ?fife=w300-rw'),
